  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine goes best with grilled versus pan-seared steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled steaks develop smoky, charred flavors that pair excellently with wines that have earthy or smoky notes like Syrah, Zinfandel, or aged Rioja. Pan-seared steaks in butter create richer, more refined flavors that complement elegant wines like Bordeaux blends or Burgundy. The cooking method significantly impacts which wine characteristics will harmonize best with your steak.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good budget-friendly wine for steak night?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Côtes du Rhône, Portuguese Douro reds, or Spanish Monastrell wines in the $15-25 range that offer excellent value. These regions produce full-bodied, food-friendly wines with the tannin structure needed for steak without the premium price of Napa Cabernet. Argentine Malbec and Washington State Cabernet Sauvignon also provide great steak-pairing potential at reasonable prices.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you pair white wine with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, full-bodied white wines can work beautifully with certain steak preparations, especially lighter cuts or cream-based sauces. Rich, oaked Chardonnay pairs well with filet mignon with béarnaise sauce, while aged white Rioja complements grilled steak with herbs. The key is choosing whites with enough weight and complexity to stand up to the beef's flavors.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing wine with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing wines that are too light or serving red wine too warm. Light-bodied wines like basic Pinot Grigio get completely overwhelmed by steak's rich flavors, while overly warm red wine tastes alcoholic and unbalanced. Always match the wine's body and intensity to your steak cut, and serve reds at proper cellar temperature for the best pairing experience.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does steak seasoning affect wine pairing choices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Bold seasonings like peppercorns call for spicy wines like Syrah or Zinfandel that can match the heat, while herb-crusted steaks pair beautifully with earthy wines like Sangiovese or Loire Valley reds. Sweet glazes or barbecue sauces work well with fruit-forward wines like Malbec or Australian Shiraz. Consider your seasoning as seriously as your steak cut when selecting wine.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant wine before serving with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young, tannic red wines like Cabernet Sauvignon, Bordeaux, or Barolo benefit significantly from 30-60 minutes of decanting before serving with steak. This aeration softens harsh tannins and opens up the wine's flavors, creating a more harmonious pairing. Older wines (10+ years) should be decanted carefully just before serving to separate sediment without over-aerating delicate flavors.</p>
